ABSTRACT

Kickstarter is a popular website that allows individuals to support others in the creation of their work. While some campaigns are successful in gaining monetary support, others are not. This study aims to determine how Kickstarter defines a successful campaign, and if there are any factors that contribute to making some campaigns more successful than others. Additionally, popularity of campaign categories on Kickstarter will be examined, as well as any time trends that exists in campaign creation. With more information about how to make a successful campaign, individuals considering their own Kickstarter campaign will be armed with more data they can use to potentially increase their chances of success.

INTRODUCTION

The crowdfunding website Kickstarter allows creative individuals to share their projects and gain funding from supporters (referred to as backers). Creators set their own monetary goal that would allow them to get their project off the ground, which backers can then pledge money in order to help the creator develop their project. However, backers will not be charged if the creator’s goal is not met. Therefore, the risk of not meeting the campaign goal is large for creators, since if their goal is not met, they do not receive any of the funding pledged. Creators can incentivize backers to contribute to their project monetarily by offering them benefits such as something they have produced if their goal is met (Leland, 2022).

The main questions examined in this study include the most and least popular campaign categories on Kickstarter, as well as the most and least successful campaign categories, and how Kickstarter defines success. Time trends in campaign creation and pledge amounts will also be examined. Additionally, this study aims to determine whether certain campaign categories are significantly more successful than others. Insights gained from this analysis could have applications for both Kickstarter as a company, and individuals attempting to launch a successful crowdfunded creative endeavor.

DATA AND METHODOLOGY

This study examines the ICPSR 38050 data set, which is a compilation of every Kickstarter campaign between 2009 (Kickstarter’s launch year) and 2020, totaling 506,199 campaigns. As the data set contains information on every campaign within this timeframe, the data set is considered a Kickstarter census. The data set includes information such as campaign category, pledge amount, backer count, campaign launch date, and location. Project names are unavailable in this data set to protect individual anonymity.

The main variables of interest in this study are numerous. Campaign category with regard to success count and success rates are examined. Additionally, this study aims to determine how Kickstarter defines success within their campaigns, and if there are any factors that contribute to a campaign’s success. No data was omitted from this study. While there was missing information, the missingness was limited to variables not examined in this study, such as location and backer count.

Additional variables were created throughout the course of the exploratory data process in the search for variable relationships and trends. For example, the difference between amount pledged and goal amount was calculated and added to the data set. Additionally, count information was tabulated to create another data set containing success and failure counts, and success and failure rates as a percentage of total campaign count. Though some code is hidden in this rendered report, all code is available and reproducible in the source Rmd.

Results indicate that the most popular year for Kickstarter was 2015, with a total of 77,835 campaigns versus only 35,548 for the most recent year for which data is available (Fig. 1).

However, the total amount pledged (Fig. 2), as well as the amount pledged per campaign (Fig. 3), on Kickstarter peaked in 2020, despite having less than half of the total campaigns created in 2015. The proportion of amount pledged to total campaign count in 2020 is significantly larger than that of 2015, however, as the data set used in a census of all Kickstarter campaigns, this could be inflated by the large quantity of overall campaigns.

With regard to campaign categories, results indicate that the most popular category on Kickstarter in total number of campaigns is Film & Video, and the least popular is Dance (Fig. 4).

When analyzing the count of successful Kickstarter campaigns (Fig. 5), results indicate that Film & Video as well as Music are the most successful in terms of overall success count. Additionally, Journalism and Dance are the categories that have the least amount of successful campaigns.

However, the fact that the categories with the highest number of successful campaigns are also those with the greatest number of total campaigns indicate that this should not be the only metric by which success is measured. For example, when investigating whether a correlation exists between total campaign number and success campaign count by category, a moderately strong linear correlation was observed (Fig. 6). 84.5% of the variance in campaign success can be explained by total campaign number. This relationship is also statistically significant with a p-value < 0.05 which means that overall campaign count has a strong effect on successful campaign count as would be expected.

Alternatively, results are also presented in the ratio of successful campaigns to the total number of campaigns in each category (Fig. 7). These results show a more standardized interpretation of true success rates, as for example, even though Dance had the fewest number of total campaigns and a low number of successful campaigns compared to other categories, the actual success rate of Dance demonstrates that it is the most successful category on Kickstarter with regard to percentage of total campaigns.

Success rates vary widely between categories, with a highest success rate of 0.62 and a lowest of 0.21. Further, a test to determine whether category has an effect on whether or not a campaign is successful (Chi-squared test of independence) indicated that success and failure rates are not independent of campaign category. This means that the chance of having a successful or failed campaign is dependent on which category the campaign is in.

These results prompted an investigation into how Kickstarter defines success. Successful Kickstarter campaigns are defined by a positive difference between the pledged amount and the goal amount, as shown in Figure 8.

When the proportion of successful campaigns and failed campaigns were examined, in relation to the total number of campaigns, the results show that Kickstarter had significantly more failed campaigns. The proportion of successful and failed campaigns were 0.38 and 0.5, respectively, which is a statistically significant difference. However, the statistical significance could potentially be inflated by the overall large scale of the data set itself.

Next, the effect of campaign goal on pledged amount for successful campaigns was examined for all Kickstarter categories (Fig. 9). The logarithm of the goal and pledge amounts were taken to create a better-fitting model, as linearity was not apparent otherwise. A moderately strong, positive linear relationship was found between goal amount and pledged amount, meaning that for successful campaigns the higher the goal of a campaign, the higher the pledged amount in general. The adjusted R-squared value indicates that 80.2% of the variation in pledge amount can be attributed to goal amount. Additionally, when categories were compared, all categories showed a similarly strong positive correlation between goal amount and pledged amount except for the Comics category, which indicates that goal amount is less of a predictor of pledged amount for this category alone. However, the linear model is less accurate at the extremes: smaller values and larger values. Therefore, caution should be taken when using this model to predict pledge amounts when goals are at the extreme, either very small or very large.

CONCLUSION

Results indicate that successful Kickstarter campaigns are those in which the amount pledged exceeds the goal set by the creator. Kickstarter has significantly more campaigns that fail to meet their goal than succeed in this endeavor. Additionally, the rate of success varies significantly depending on the category of the campaign. For example, Dance had the highest rate of success while technology had the lowest. Results also indicated that in successful campaigns, higher goals are strongly correlated with higher pledge amounts, but that this trend is not as strong for very high or very low goals.

While popularity in sheer number of campaign trends peaked in 2015, the amount pledged has actually been growing throughout the years, peaking in 2020. Further, the amount of money pledged per campaign has also increased to its 2020 peak. This could be due to a variety of factors, including the effects of the Covid-19 pandemic. Time in lock-down allowed many individuals increased leisure time, which could have prompted them to find creative projects on Kickstarter that they wished to contribute to. Additionally, the effect of the stimulus payments could have provided individuals with an increased ability to support these creative projects.

Recommendations for anyone considering creating a Kickstarter campaign are numerous. First, category should be taken into account when starting a campaign, as success rates vary widely across categories. Second, results indicate that the monetary goal should be set at a moderate amount. The goal needs to be attainable for campaigns to be considered successful and to receive the pledge money. Additionally, results indicated that for successful campaigns goal amount is positively correlated with pledge amount, and that this is the most true for moderate goals that are not extremely low or extremely high. Therefore, goals should be attainable, but not too low.

2-proportion z-test assumptions: 1) np ≥ 10 & n(1-p) ≥ 10 (n sufficiently large): Use #1: This assumption is met as all samples are quite large Use #2: Met for the same reason as Use #1 2) Independence within and between groups: Use #1: Campaigns were either made in 2015, or 2020 (not both), so this is met. Additionally, one campaign being made in 2015 does not affect the chance of another being created in the same year. Therefore, this assumption is met. Use #2: A campaign can only succeed or fail, not both, so independence across groups is satisfied. Additionally, a campaign in one category succeeding does not affect the chances of success of another campaign in the same category. Therefore, this assumption is also met. 3) Sample can’t be more than 10% of population: Use #1: While the sample size is quite large, it is still safe to say that less than 10% of the global population has a Kickstarter campaign made between 2009 and 2020. Therefore, this assumption is also met Use #2: Met for the same reason as Use #1

Chi-Squared Test of Independence: 1) Count data 2) Independence assumption: If the expected and observed counts for each cell deviate significantly, it provides evidence that the two variables are not independent. While the expected and observed counts do vary, they don’t appear to vary enough to conclude that categories are not independent from one another. Additionally, the chance of a campaign in one category being successful does not affect the chances of a campaign in another category being successful. Therefore, this is met. 3) Each expected count is at least 5: This assumption is met (see below)
